13.31	Deportation_of_Koreans_in_the_Soviet_Union	Deportation of Koreans in the Soviet Union	Approximately 100,000 Koreans were deported to Kazakhstan and 74,000 were sent to Uzbekistan. Many Koreans were placed far from each other in isolation to prevent contact with each other. 34,000 Koreans were placed on the desolate outpost of Ushtobe, Kazakhstan with no food and no shelter and were forced to survive on their own for almost three years. Thousands died of starvation, sickness and exposure during the first the first few years in Central Asia. The ethnic Kazakhs were essential during these first few years for the Koreans. They provided shelter and food to help the Koreans suffering from starvation and cold.	
